Subject: If Youre New to Data, Read This Before You Build Anything
Body Text:
View this post on the web at https://seattledataguy.substack.com/p/if-youre-new-to-data-read-this-before

Hi, fellow future and current Data Leaders; Ben here 
Today, were going to discuss how you can improve communication with the business to gain buy-in for a project or deliver better results and insights.
Before doing that, I wanted to let you know that in July, Ill be hosting several webinars and discussions with data leaders about problems that extend beyond just technology (although well likely touch on some infrastructure topics). So, if youre interested in growing as a data leader, you can sign up here [ https://substack.com/redirect/bd4b4a2b-b3ec-479f-9e7a-5813f96f41c9?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ].
Now, lets jump into the article!
When youre just getting started in data, everything feels exciting, and everything sounds like a good idea.
"Oh, this process takes ten minutes? Ill automate it with VBA!"
Fast-forward four weeks, and youre trying to meet the finance team's expectations, reconciling numbers, and banging your head against a table, wondering why you ever volunteered.
New paradigms show up with shiny names and polished diagrams. They sound smart. Youve got nothing to compare them to, so you try them. After all, everyone else seems to be.
Thats what this article is about: the things I wish I understood earlier in my data career. It started because there were so many buzzwords and new products popping up in the past few weeks, it might not be clear whats actually going on if youre new to the data space.
Whether youre early in your data career or just want a sanity check, heres a breakdown of the stuff that actually matters (and the fluff that doesnt).
Lets dive in.
1) Avoid Being The Only Engineer On A Team Early On In Your Career
My very first role out of college was working for a finance team as their tech person. That work ranged from creating Tableau reports and building ETLs [ https://substack.com/redirect/5f53cd87-f2ee-4a70-ba80-aa736413a297?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] in SSIS [ https://substack.com/redirect/1fa35fa0-e9d0-49aa-a31e-f619182e29b4?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] to taking over a C# MVC site, one no one mentioned until about two months in.
I learned a lot in that role, but not much about how to actually develop. Sure, I built dashboards [ https://substack.com/redirect/f8cc85c3-e2a6-4e9b-a0a4-1c3346ce5cc1?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] and picked up the quirks of SSIS [ https://substack.com/redirect/c165778a-14d6-4204-8d33-84895b3ad332?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]. But being the only developer early in your career isnt just isolating, it limits your growth.
You miss out on design reviews. You dont get to hear other peoples experiences or perspectives. Youre stuck with what you already know.
If you can, look for roles where youll work alongside other engineers, especially ones with more experience. Theyll share why they made certain decisions, review your code, and offer feedback that helps you level up.
That will grow you far more than a job that hands you shiny tech or gives you free reign with no guidance.
Seek out a strong engineering culture.
SeattleDataGuys Newsletter is a reader-supported publication. To receive new posts and support my work, consider becoming a free or paid subscriber.
2) Hype Wont Fix Your Business Problems
Theres always been a lot of fluff in tech, but over the past few years, its gotten louder. Vendors have started leaning hard into new design patterns, terms, and products, all packaged as solutions.
How many combinations of Lake, House, Ware, Compute, and a dozen other buzzwords can we toss into a blender and call it innovation?
Honestly, many of these terms have started to lose meaning. The problem is, if youre just getting started, its easy to get hooked. Youve got no baseline for what came before, and early in your career, youre probably focused more on solving technical problems than business ones. So, the jargon sounds legit.
It sounds like it solves something. And vendors work hard to make sure it does. They script their pitches to speak directly to engineers pain points, while conveniently ignoring others.
Theyve got polished diagrams and their reasoning can sound solid. Pretty soon, were all parroting these new terms and patterns, often for ideas that have been around for years.
Its just Vendor-Driven Design. [ https://substack.com/redirect/39b47c25-771d-4d0c-a6fc-98b451e0b029?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
3) Solving Business Problems Is Hard
Most of us tech folks spend a lot of time learning the tech and not much time understanding the business [ https://substack.com/redirect/dc391072-0db6-457b-bcb5-9bfdf847ddd8?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]. In some ways, that makes sense. The technical problems were solving are hard, and its not always easy to hit pause and zoom out.
But the risk is real: you can end up in an ivory tower of wayward data wizards, building cool stuff that doesnt actually solve anything. Or maybe you build something that kind of works. Well even the best models or flashiest AI wont matter if they dont translate into the real world.
Just ask Zillow [ https://substack.com/redirect/2d6d746b-a5a3-4c02-94d1-69bf6712a3fa?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ].
Business is hard. Dont believe me? Quit your job and try starting [ https://substack.com/redirect/55de6d78-c140-4fae-8f36-201451ca5752?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] anything. Theres no such thing as an easy business. And just because you have data doesnt mean youll magically uncover insights no one else has found.
4) Dont Skip The Fundamentals 
I talk about this a lot because its still true: the fundamentals matter.
Its why Ive been writing so many articles that talk about going back to the basics [ https://substack.com/redirect/c7bbec20-d544-4f15-b408-dfeea9edb325?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]. We can be so focused on building something new that we dont check if the foundation is solid. 
Even the most advanced infrastructure will fail if its built on sand.
Sure, AI can automate some things and help code. But Im still working on projects where the basics are absolutely required. People still want to pull data from an SFTP [ https://substack.com/redirect/aa3a9d88-6d85-4da9-8a01-36ed6e767391?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] and load it into a warehouse. You still need to deal with IAM [ https://substack.com/redirect/b505d2b6-462c-48ce-be40-343ed63e25e5?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] issues (still a pain). You still need to understand data modeling [ https://substack.com/redirect/7b543ded-7f87-4f89-9581-87753183e868?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] and of course people still are struggling to answer key questions about their business. None of that has changed.
The ability to apply foundational skills to more complex problemsat scale or across systems with tons of integrationsstill matters.
So, build a solid base. Dont rush. Theres plenty of time to become a senior engineer. [ https://substack.com/redirect/3cf9b444-a874-4b46-bd10-2c83fcd3f4b8?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
5) Dont Be Above Putting in the Work
Some people get truly lucky, their family knows someone, they roll a nat 20 on charisma, or life just lines up. Most people arent that lucky. 
If youre like most of us, youll need to earn your stripes by taking on work that:
Feels repetitive or less exciting than your school projects
Doesnt show up on highlight reels but keeps systems running
Builds the foundation for deeper, more complex skills later on
We now live in a world where AI can take a lot of grunt work off our plates. Migrating [ https://substack.com/redirect/a1e2cac7-e8c1-48c6-9763-c2749cd5cc5c?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] SQL Server to Snowflake [ https://substack.com/redirect/4b2643b0-4819-4196-b5bf-4ae0b0298974?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]? Way easier than it used to be. I remember sinking way too much time into converting Oracle to SQL Server. Sure, there were tools that helped, but they never got it all the way there.
Whatever the grunt work looks like:
Dont act like youre above it
Use it as a chance to learn how things really work
And if you think the process is broken? Improve it
6) Ask Why - But Dont Always Expect A Great Answer
We can be so focused early on in our careers on growing technically that we forget to ask an important question. Why are we even doing the work? Does it actually add value to the business? 
Im not naive enough to think its always that simple. If you ask why youll be bestowed years upon years of wisdom and business acumen. 
Sometimes, your manager is asking you to do something because their bosss boss told them to, and theyre just trying to keep their job.
That doesnt mean you shouldnt ask. You might learn something about the business. Or, at the very least, gain some empathy for the pressure your boss is under.
So yes, ask why. Just dont expect it to end the conversation, or magically lead to a dynamic shift in the types of requests youre going to get.
7) Learn to Communicate with Non-Data People
A lot of advice around communication is vague at best. Just get better at communicating!
But what does that even mean?
In my experience, there are a few key areas where most of us can improve:
Know your audience: A huge part of communication is understanding who youre talking to. The best leaders and engineers Ive worked with are constantly asking, Who is this message for? Thats not an exaggeration. I once invited a data leader to join a live session I was hosting, thinking wed just have a casual chat. Instead, we spent a good hour prepping, discussing the audience, what they needed to hear, and what takeaways mattered most.
Lead with the point: When we deliver analysis [ https://substack.com/redirect/31446e60-077e-4866-a177-ba5f18f11f57?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] (or really any information), many of us, myself included, tend to talk through our entire process first. We want to prove how smart we are. But stakeholders dont need the play-by-play; they need the takeaway. Say the conclusion up front, then explain how you got there if needed.
Pre-wire key conversations: If you're about to share something controversial, surprising, or high-stakes, dont wait for the meeting. Send a preview. Talk to one or two key stakeholders ahead of time. Youll smooth over objections and get more useful feedback.
If youd like to dig deeper, check out this past article:
Final Thoughts
Whether you're new to data or have been in the space for years, youll always be learning. Youll get better at communicating your message. Youll keep reassessing tooling, asking whether something actually improves how you work or if its just more marketing fluff.
And thats the point: you dont need to have it all figured out straight out of the gate. Even knowing something doesnt mean it's easy to apply. As one data leader recently told me, You can know it, but having the discipline to put it into practice is a whole different story.
Before signing off, I wanted to share a few articles worth reading if youre just getting started. Theyll help you make sense of how the tech world has evolvedand what hasnt changed at all.
7 Articles I Think Everyone in Data Should Read
Dont Let Architecture Astronauts Scare You [ https://substack.com/redirect/61dbf077-b57c-42c3-934e-d8d19182e26d?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
The Politics of Data Warehousing [ https://substack.com/redirect/f1243024-242c-4b8d-9b3d-d69c60905c14?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Is Kimball Still Relevant? [ https://substack.com/redirect/d6b265b8-caff-4283-98a6-3b9e5dc7910e?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] by Joe Reis  
The Marketing Behind MongoDB [ https://substack.com/redirect/c5078532-9282-43ca-a7d8-779fd63e5907?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
A Critique of the SQL Database Language [ https://substack.com/redirect/7baafc1b-973c-479d-8de2-eee2fa5ed444?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Functional Data Engineering  a modern paradigm for batch data processing [ https://substack.com/redirect/c0e1e606-69da-4e7a-a6b1-bbb5ccdefc55?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Big Ball of Mud [ https://substack.com/redirect/8bbbe3df-332d-4f4e-b3fa-a1fdba0f5b3e?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] - Architectural Devolution
Video Of The Week - Data Engineers Vs Data Analysts - How Data Engineers Write SQL Vs Analysts
Join My Data Engineering And Data Science Discord
If youre looking to talk more about data engineering, data science, breaking into your first job, and finding other like minded data specialists. Then you should join the Seattle Data Guy discord!
We are now over 8000 members!
Join My Technical Consultants Community
If youre a data consultant or considering becoming one then you should join the Technical Freelancer Community! We have over 1700 members!
Youll find plenty of free resources you can access to expedite your journey as a technical consultant as well as be able to talk to other consultants about questions you may have!
Articles Worth Reading
There are thousands of new articles posted daily all over the web! I have spent a lot of time sifting through some of these articles as well as TechCrunch and companies tech blog and wanted to share some of my favorites!
Model Once, Represent Everywhere: UDA (Unified Data Architecture) at Netflix
As Netflixs offerings grow  across films, series, games, live events, and ads  so does the complexity of the systems that support it. Core business concepts like actor or movie are modeled in many places: in our Enterprise GraphQL Gateway powering internal apps, in our asset management platform storing media assets, in our media computing platform that powers encoding pipelines, to name a few. Each system models these concepts differently and in isolation, with little coordination or shared understanding. While they often operate on the same concepts, these systems remain largely unaware of that fact, and of each other.
Read More Here [ https://substack.com/redirect/94e83874-19ee-4442-8af3-af7ef7e8f03e?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Why Your Data Stack Won't Last - And How To Build Data Infrastructure That Will
As a consultant, I have been called in to review and, in many cases, replace dozens of half-finished, abandoned, and sometimes forgotten data infrastructure projects.
The data infrastructure in a few cases may just need a little tweaking to operate effectively, but other times the project is either so incomplete or so lacking in a central design that the best thing to do is replace the old system.
Trust me, Id love it if I could come into a project and simply change a few lines of code, and then everything would just work. However, so many projects are filled with unclear design decisions or resume-driven development that were never rooted in good planning.
Read More Here [ https://substack.com/redirect/4cf0186c-ee3c-4a35-a07a-ed4478fb4a39?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
End Of Day 184
Thanks for checking out our community. We put out 4-5 Newsletters a month discussing data, tech, and start-ups.
If you enjoyed it, consider liking, sharing and helping this newsletter grow!

Subject: My mom's lesson on standing out
Body Text:
A ProFellow newsletter from Dr. Vicki Johnson Dear readers, Today we celebrate Mother's Day in the U.S. I am sending a note of love to my Mom, and to all other moms, grandmothers, aunties, friends, and caregivers of all types who provide comfort and nurturing to others. When I speak about my MATCH ME Formula, the 7 elements of a winning application, I often share that I learned the art of storytelling from my dad, who is an experienced writer and speaker. But it wasn't until I started writing my forthcoming book, _Pitch Your Potential_ [https://profellow.krtra.com/c/Dd82U94vFKrK/xeLlP], that I realized some of the profound lessons that my mom taught me that helped me become a great applicant and career contender. My mom was trained as a nurse, but she stayed home to care for us when my siblings and I were young. Finances were tight. Our family of 5 was supported by my dad's sole salary as a minister at a small church. My mom always had a passion for interior design, antiques, and art history. Although she had very limited resources to purchase decor, she had a defined vision and eye for her decorating style, which I would describe as Victorian-era country living. Our home displayed family heirlooms and wall art, feminine curtains and stenciling, and layered textures in throw pillows, patterned china, and handmade patchwork quilts. There were many vintage items and furniture made from distressed wood and weathered metals that she carefully selected from thrift stores and antique shops. Thanks to my mom, our house was also uncluttered and very clean, which made it comfortable. I remember this because I was the one tasked with cleaning our bathroom for an hour every week as soon as I was old enough to handle a scrub brush! I can now appreciate why. When I was a teenager, I started to notice that my home was quite different from my friends homes because it was more organized and detailed than most. Most of my friends homes held a collection of well-loved furniture and personal things, but without any particular theme. Some friends homes had a more polished look that mirrored a favorite department store, but lacked originality. When I noticed this difference in our homes, it got me thinking about the power of attention to detail and creativity. I have always admired the detail in my mom's selection of colors, textures, and groupings to create beautiful interior designs, and other people did as well. At age 43, she finally pursued and achieved her Bachelor's degree in Art History, receiving the distinction of magna cum laude. She went on to work in boutiques and museums, including Winterthur, a historic DuPont mansion, where she had the chance to apply her skills and eye for design professionally. I realized you can gain positive attention and become memorable when you create something that has high detail, especially when those creations demonstrate that you are paying attention to the desires of your audience. Think of a fancy restaurant or a beautiful wedding you attended. What you notice and enjoy are the small, highly curated details. FROM MY MOM'S EXAMPLE, I LEARNED THAT BEING HIGHLY SPECIFIC - APPLYING HIGH DETAIL IN MY APPLICATIONS - IS A MAGIC INGREDIENT FOR GETTING NOTICED AND BECOMING A TOP CONTENDER. Creating an application that is highly specific doesnt require a lot of resources. It just requires time, creativity, and the practiced skill of curation. We value something thats one-of-a-kind more than something that is common or mass-produced because it's special. Likewise, you make your application special by including specific details in every aspect of your pitch: in your stories, your background and skills, the ideas you propose, and why you desire the opportunity. This is why the "H" in the MATCH ME Formula, the 7 elements of a winning application, stands for "Highly Specific." This week's tip comes from my dear Mom: _Think about how you can add more detail to each sentence in your application to make your application more noticeable and eye-catching. Add detail to your career goal, the story of your background, and the vision of your future impact._ __ Happy Mother's Day readers! Warm regards, Vicki Dr. Vicki Johnson Founder, ProFellow __Author of_Pitch Your Potential [https://profellow.krtra.com/c/Dd82U94vFKrK/xeLlP](coming soon!)_ Visit my website [https://profellow.krtra.com/c/isBdhnX3N2Yf/xeLlP] Make your application special by including specific details in every aspect of your pitch. Subject: [Day 3 Assignments] 5-Day Gen AI Intensive
Body Text:
Kaggle


Hello Candace,

 Today's Assignment

1. Complete Unit 3a - Generative AI Agents:


Listen to the summary podcast episode for this unit.
To complement the podcast, read the Generative AI Agents whitepaper.
Complete these codelabs on Kaggle:


Talk to a database with function calling.
Build an agentic ordering system in LangGraph.


2. [Optional] Advanced 3b - Agents Companion:


Listen to the summary podcast episode for this unit.
Read the advanced Agents Companion whitepaper.
Want to have an interactive conversation? Try adding the whitepaper toNotebookLM.

 What You'll Learn

Learn to build sophisticated AI agents by understanding their corecomponents and the iterative development process. You'll also learn moreabout advanced agentic architectures and approaches such as multi-agentsystems, agent evaluation and more.

The codelabs cover how to connect LLMs to existing systems and to the realworld. Learn about function calling by giving SQL tools to a chatbot(including an example using Gemini 2.0's Live API), and learn how to builda LangGraph agent that takes orders in a caf.

 Reminders and Announcements


Find a complete list of scheduled livestreams and past recordings here.

The next livestream is tomorrow at 11 AM PT / 7 PM CET / 11:30 PM IST.Click here to join! Livestream guests: Alan Blount, Antonio Gulli, StevenJohnson, Jaclyn Konzelmann, Patrick Marlow, Anant Nawalgaria and JuliaWiesinger.
Be sure to ask all your questions about the podcast, readings, and codelabsin the #5dgai-question-forum channel on Discord. You'll get Kaggle swag ifyour question is chosen for discussion during the livestream.

Happy learning and see you tomorrow!

The Kaggle Team








Google

 2025 Kaggle, Inc 1600 Amphitheatre Pkwy Mountain View, CA 94043

In times of change, learners inherit the earth while the learned find themselves beautifully equipped to deal with a world that no longer exists.

 Eric Hoffer, Philospher



Have You Heard?

News, updates and guides from the world of creativity.

[The Imagination Age: Why Creativity is the Currency of the Future](https://click.skillshare.com/z/h8128j6w04z104?uid=2c97bae7-cbb0-4ca7-8393-acdc2aab0b63&txnid=3e225136-71a6-4ae5-bd2f-edea0782529d&mid=85375515-8ed0-4cb3-8e3d-4e5537dc4bbc&bsft_aaid=d5edc627-0f6f-46e0-b492-6ae0d9cbe64a&bsft_ek=2025-06-24T14%3A00%3A13Z&bsft_mime_type=text&bsft_tv=19&bsft_lx=12)

In a world where AI can write code, generate content, and automate tasks in seconds, its fair to wonder: where does that leave me?! Deep breath. Were not entering a post-human futurewere stepping into the Imagination Age, where creativity, empathy, and original thinking are the most valuable tools youve got. The machines might be fast, but the future still belongs to those who can imagine whats next.

-  Creativity is no longer a niche skillits your most future-proof asset
- The ability to imagine, invent, and dream beyond the brief is what AI cant replicate
-  Staying curious and committed to lifelong learning will keep your creativity sharp and evolving

[Read the Full Article](https://click.skillshare.com/z/h8128j6w04z104?uid=2c97bae7-cbb0-4ca7-8393-acdc2aab0b63&txnid=3e225136-71a6-4ae5-bd2f-edea0782529d&mid=85375515-8ed0-4cb3-8e3d-4e5537dc4bbc&bsft_aaid=d5edc627-0f6f-46e0-b492-6ae0d9cbe64a&bsft_ek=2025-06-24T14%3A00%3A13Z&bsft_mime_type=text&bsft_tv=19&bsft_lx=13)



[The traits that will define the next generation of creative leaders](https://click.skillshare.com/z/hj1j8j610h4704?uid=2c97bae7-cbb0-4ca7-8393-acdc2aab0b63&txnid=3e225136-71a6-4ae5-bd2f-edea0782529d&mid=85375515-8ed0-4cb3-8e3d-4e5537dc4bbc&bsft_aaid=d5edc627-0f6f-46e0-b492-6ae0d9cbe64a&bsft_ek=2025-06-24T14%3A00%3A13Z&bsft_mime_type=text&bsft_tv=19&bsft_lx=14)

If imagination is the new currency, these are the traits that will help you spend it wisely. As the creative landscape shifts, success wont just belong to those who can makebut to those who can think critically, lead confidently, and adapt with purpose. From emotional intelligence to purpose-driven thinking, these are the qualities shaping tomorrows most impactful creative leaders.

-  Adaptability: the tools will change, the brief will shiftyour superpower will be to stay flexible in the face of change and uncertainty
-  Taste: while anyone can create, those with taste will be able to curateknowing what to kill, keep, or push forward
-  Emotional intelligence: as creativity becomes more automated, leading with empathy and awareness is what will set you apart

[Read the Full Article](https://click.skillshare.com/z/hj1j8j610h4704?uid=2c97bae7-cbb0-4ca7-8393-acdc2aab0b63&txnid=3e225136-71a6-4ae5-bd2f-edea0782529d&mid=85375515-8ed0-4cb3-8e3d-4e5537dc4bbc&bsft_aaid=d5edc627-0f6f-46e0-b492-6ae0d9cbe64a&bsft_ek=2025-06-24T14%3A00%3A13Z&bsft_mime_type=text&bsft_tv=19&bsft_lx=15)

Goal-Time-Money

So, I dropped a new video breaking down exactly how it works:

Why identifying your true priority is the only way to make real progress
How to become aware of the trade-offs in any decision you make
The simple way to avoid the trap of staying stuck, spinning your wheels

Chat soon,

Subject: Missing something, Candace?
Body Text:
Ever feel like your work is missing something deeper, Candace?



That's where Shahinaz was 12 years ago too.



Even though she was successful in her humanitarian career, Shahinaz felt like she could be doing something deeper.



Then she discovered life coaching.



It opened doors for her to get more fulfillment from her career - and offer a new level of impact for the people she helps.

Subject: Praise for 'Pitch Your Potential' & BONUS events
Body Text:
>From Dr. Vicki Johnson, Founder, ProFellow [https://profellow.krtra.com/c/O1Kg4bu0WRdT/xeLlP] Dear ProFellow readers, In January, Wiley is publishing my first book: Pitch Your Potential: The Formula for Winning Dream Jobs, Awards, and Elite Opportunities [https://profellow.krtra.com/c/O1Kg4bu0WRdT/xeLlP]! _Pitch Your Potential_ is an in-depth guide to the MATCH ME Formulathe 7 elements of a winning applicationthat I have taught for years in ProFellow courses and workshops. The book is a tactical guide on how to confidently tell your story in job, university, and fellowship applications using approaches anyone can apply. I'm pleased to share that I've received praise for the book from leaders in the fellowship industry: >_"Iveseenthousandsoffoundersandworld-classstorytellers >throughmyworkasaninvestorandinourcompetitiveMilestone >Makerprogram,andVickisprocessissecondtonone.'PitchYour >Potential'distillsherbrillianceintoaplaybookthatwill >transformhowyoutellyourstoryandopendoorsyounever >imagined."_ - NICOLA CORZINE, Founding CEO of the Nasdaq Entrepreneurial Center and the competitive Milestone Makers program >_Vickioffersapowerfulguidetotellingyourstorywith >authenticitywhileunlockingopportunitiesyouoncethoughtwereout >ofreach.Thisisessentialreadingforyoungprofessionalspursuing >graduatestudyandsteppingintoleadershipinpublicservice._ - JORGE LUIS PANIAGUA VALLE, Chief Operating Officer at Govern for America >_"Havingworkedwithchangemakersaroundtheworld,Iknowhowvital >itistocommunicateyouruniquevalue.'PitchYourPotential' >distillsthatskillintoanaccessible,inspiringformulathatwill >helpyoubecomeanabove-and-beyondcandidate."_ - ROSHAN PAUL, Executive Director of Surge Climate Talent, and best-selling author of _The New Reason to Work_ PRE-ORDER BONUS FOR PROFELLOW READERS I am giving 3 exclusive webinars this Fall just for those of you who pre-order my book Pitch Your Potential [https://profellow.krtra.com/c/O1Kg4bu0WRdT/xeLlP]. ONE BOOK PRE-ORDER GETS YOU INTO ALL 3 EVENTS! You'll learn the MATCH ME Formulathe 7 elements of a winning applicationand how to apply this Formula to graduate school, fellowship and job applications NOW! The BONUS events are: OCT. 23, 10AM PT (_NOTE NEW DATE_): How to Become a TOP CANDIDATE FOR GRADUATE SCHOOL using the MATCH ME Formula [https://profellow.krtra.com/c/U73nfosbQmCp/xeLlP] Learn how to create a master's or doctoral application that is _Memorable_, _Highly specific_, & _Capitalizes on their unique benefits_ NOV. 21, 10AM PT: How to Create an EXCEPTIONAL FELLOWSHIP APPLICATION using the MATCH ME Formula [https://profellow.krtra.com/c/ROUseM2h7WXc/xeLlP] Learn how to create a fellowship proposal that is _Timely & urgent_, and _Elegant_ DEC. 19, 10AM PT: How to Stand Out in the COMPETITIVE JOB MARKET using the MATCH ME Formula [https://profellow.krtra.com/c/U2zvQAd8fTa4/xeLlP] Learn how to create a pitch that _Aligns with their mission_ and is _Mutually beneficial_ These events are for people at ALL career levels, and will be an intimate opportunity for you to spend time with me and ProFellow's biggest fans. Don't miss these events! HOW TO REDEEM To get registered for this Pitch Your Potential Webinar Series: 1. PRE-ORDER THE BOOK "PITCH YOUR POTENTIAL". You can buy from: Amazon [https://www.amazon.com/Pitch-Your-Potential-Formula-Opportunities/dp/1394328265/ref=sr_1_1?crid=O5XCEUL6M8RO&dib=eyJ2IjoiMSJ9.Kr_FUDioO4ZdK17foAilJw.L39vdn1SvP1bOkhOH22YQuRUMFQyhGm0gyNiIfsAVNw&dib_tag=se&keywords=9781394328260&qid=1750768418&sprefix=9781394328260%2Caps%2C161&sr=8-1&kuid=71f94d97-3f07-413c-908d-5cf766b7f194-1758059543&kref=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.drvickijohnson.com%2Fbook] ( global shipping) | Barnes & Noble [https://www.barnesandnoble.com/w/pitch-your-potential-vicki-johnson/1147525485?ean=9781394328260&kuid=71f94d97-3f07-413c-908d-5cf766b7f194-1758059543&kref=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.drvickijohnson.com%2Fbook] | Bookshop.org [https://bookshop.org/p/books/pitch-your-potential-the-formula-for-winning-dream-jobs-awards-and-elite-opportunities-vicki-johnson/4aba58cc5639399c?ean=9781394328260&next=t&next=t%2Ct&kuid=71f94d97-3f07-413c-908d-5cf766b7f194-1758059543&kref=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.drvickijohnson.com%2Fbook] | Books-a-Million [https://www.booksamillion.com/p/Pitch-Your-Potential/Vicki-Johnson/9781394328260?kuid=71f94d97-3f07-413c-908d-5cf766b7f194-1758059543&kref=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.drvickijohnson.com%2Fbook] | Porchlight [https://www.porchlightbooks.com/products/pitch-your-potential-vicki-johnson-9781394328260?_pos=1&_sid=a792d0228&_ss=r&kuid=71f94d97-3f07-413c-908d-5cf766b7f194-1758059543&kref=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.drvickijohnson.com%2Fbook] (discount group orders!) 2. EMAIL A SCREENSHOT OF YOUR CONFIRMATION OR RECEIPT OF PURCHASE TO bookbonus@profellow.com. Add a message as to why you are excited to read the book! Thats it! Youll receive your event registration within one business day, and youll receive replays from the events you miss. Thank you for pre-ordering and investing an approach that will help you tell your story. I look forward to seeing you LIVE in these events! Subject: Thanks for your interest in Qventus
Body Text:
Hi Candace,



Thank you for your interest in the Analytics Lead position with Qventus. After reviewing your experience carefully against this position, we're moving ahead in our search for candidates who we feel are a closer match to what we need at this time. Of course, this doesn't mean that you might not be a great candidate for future roles with us, so we would love to keep you 'on our radar' for new opportunities as they come up.



We encourage you to continue to check for openings on our careers page and get in touch with us if you see any opportunity you are interested in! Though we're aware these messages are never welcome, we hope you appreciate knowing your status and please keep in touch!



Thank you,

Talent Acquisition at Qventus

Subject: Only 2 weeks left
Body Text:
Hey Candace,



I know its Friday and you dont want to do a lot of reading



So I promise this wont take more than 2 minutes to read.



I just came to let you know that youve only got 2 weeks left to enroll if you want to be part of my new cohort of life coaching students inside the Jay Shetty Certification School. ( https://call.jayshettycoaching.com/?el=booking-email-two-weeks-159-4&utm_campaign=booking-be&utm_campaign_name=JSCS%3A+Prospects+Week+159-4&utm_content_name=Only+2+weeks+left+%E2%8F%B0&utm_medium_name=email_action&utm_source_name=customer.io )



Between now and July



Each student in this cohort will get:



 A structured path to a rewarding new career opportunity as a certified life coach (no past experience needed)



 Full training on how to coach others using my unique, holistic approach



 Guidance from a world-class coach who has mentored 100s of would-be coaches



Together, these things will not just make you a Jay Shetty Certified Coach by July



But also open doors to more freedom and new opportunities in your career



More time and deeper relationships with your family



And a sense of security that you could earn income as a life coach from anywhere in the world (as long as there are humans).



But if you want this by July



You need toclick here and book your enrollment interview now ( https://call.jayshettycoaching.com/?el=booking-email-two-weeks-159-4&utm_campaign=booking-be&utm_campaign_name=JSCS%3A+Prospects+Week+159-4&utm_content_name=Only+2+weeks+left+%E2%8F%B0&utm_medium_name=email_action&utm_source_name=customer.io ) - so you can talk to my team about joining the school as a new student.

Subject: Re: [LAUNCH DAY] Low-Ticket Launchpad is LIVE!
Body Text:
Hey there!

Yesterday, we officially launched Low-Ticket Launchpadand the
response weve gotten so far has been AWESOME.

In fact, over 230+ people have joined and introduced themselves
to the community already:


So if you missed the launch yesterday (dont worry, we know life
is busy), heres the link to join:

-----------------------------------------------------------------
Click here to join 200+ other writers & creators inside
Low-Ticket Launchpad. (
https://click.convertkit-mail.com/v8u2pwwv82brhv4wzpwtghv4xx8llh9/g3h7elx4cwumdvwzrpa3/aHR0cHM6Ly9zaGlwLnNhbWNhcnQuY29tL3Byb2R1Y3RzL2xvdy10aWNrZXQtbGF1bmNocGFk
)
-----------------------------------------------------------------

And since we like to reward action takers, here are the free
bonuses you get when you join Low-Ticket Launchpad):

* The Viral Drop Playbook: If youve been struggling to grow your
email list organically (and sell more products), this is the
fastest, most cost-effective growth strategy weve ever
developed.

* Product Traffic Vault: If youre tired of wasting hours
creating content that gets buried by the algorithm, our Product
Traffic Vault will give you immediate access to social post
templates that actually get attention.

But now, the best part:

-----------------------------------------------------------------
We also wanted to share a handful of introductions from other
Digital Product Builders whove already joined.
-----------------------------------------------------------------

Just to give you a better sense of how diverse the group is (but
also how similar everyones goals and challenges are).

* Hey, Im Adam. The module 1 exercise is worth $350 bucks, not
here to blow smoke. I wrote 4 faulty beliefs, reframes, and the
action part is really the kicker, its so amazing to see that the
gold was hiding on the other side of the faulty beliefs all
along!

* Hey everyone, Im Patrick based in southern California.
Working on creating, launching and selling a digital product! #1
goal is to make the first sale.

* Ahoy fellow builders, Im Jamie from London. I help YouTubers
craft great video ideas and supercharge their growth through
clickable titles and thumbnails. I started as Ali Abdaals
full-time YouTube producer creating his thumbnails, titles,
coming up with video ideas and managing his scripting, and
editing teams. Now, alongside my ongoing 1-to-1 consulting, my
goal is to build my own YouTube-focused digital products and
transition into group coaching.

* Hey, Dakota from Pasadena here, an author committed to helping
other fiction authors succeed! Currently writing, but intend on
creating digital courses to help authors write quality books
faster, enjoy the process, defeat burnout, and get more stories
out there! My #1 goal with this is to earn 10k a month in net
profit from this course by the end of the year!

* Frank here! I am a sports medicine physician from Bavaria,
Germany writing educational courses. They are all about self help
for runners with overuse running injuries, as Achilles
tendinitis, anterior knee pain, shin splints.

As you can see, theres a very rich and diverse group of writers
inside Low-Ticket Launchpad.
-----------------------------------------------------------------

But they all have the same goal:

To create and sell their own $350 digital product.

So, if youd like to do the same this year (and in the future!),
wed love to give you our playbook.

-----------------------------------------------------------------
Click here to join 200+ others whove already joined Low-Ticket
Launchpad. (
https://click.convertkit-mail.com/v8u2pwwv82brhv4wzpwtghv4xx8llh9/g3h7elx4cwumdvwzrpa3/aHR0cHM6Ly9zaGlwLnNhbWNhcnQuY29tL3Byb2R1Y3RzL2xvdy10aWNrZXQtbGF1bmNocGFk
)
-----------------------------------------------------------------

See you inside!

Dickie & Cole

If you'd like to update your email settings, choose one of the
options below:

* No longer want to get updates about our new product, Low Ticket
Launchpad? Don't worryclick here to opt-out from any future
emails about this training. (
https://click.convertkit-mail.com/v8u2pwwv82brhv4wzpwtghv4xx8llh9/m2h2x5lna6u3grznvwsl/aHR0cHM6Ly92aW5lLXBlcmNoLTczMC5ub3Rpb24uc2l0ZS9Cb29tLXlvdS12ZS1vcHRlZC1vdXQtb2Ytb3VyLUxvdy1UaWNrZXQtTGF1bmNocGFkLXVwZGF0ZXMtMWMyMDFiOTU2YmI2ODBmYWI3MTRmMjkyZWQzNmRiZDI_cHZzPTQ=
)

* Don't want to receive any new emails from us (Dickie & Cole)?
Click here to unsubscribe from our email list (
https://unsubscribe.convertkit-mail.com/v8u2pwwv82brhv4wzpwtghv4xx8llh9
). (Just a heads up: You will also stop receiving updates about
any products you might've bought from us if you choose this
option!)

Subject: Get Inspired to Create New Stories and Visuals
Body Text:
844.716.1492 | fullsaildc3.com

Get Inspired to Create New Stories and Visuals
Lights, Camera, Learn!    

Learn to Create Epic Worlds on Screen

Film and television have introduced us to breathtaking worlds and storytelling experiences that convey a range of complex human emotions.

If youre inspired to become one of the artists who help create this entertainment, consider enrolling in Full Sail DC3s new six week program, The Craft of Cinematography: Mastering Visual Language, where you can explore the core elements of visual storytelling with one of the leaders in the industry.

Familiar with popular HBO series like House of the Dragon, Game of Thrones, Succession, True Detective and Westworld? Our course was designed by Emmy Award-winner Stephen Beres, who has lead production and post teams on all of these hits and more.

With Stephens guidance, you can examine how to best communicate your own unique vision throughout different stages of the production process. From camera selection to exposure and color study, this exclusive course is designed to teach you how to bring stories to life, craft stronger worlds and create powerful entertainment.

Online sessions for The Craft of Cinematography: Mastering Visual Language with Emmy Award-Winner Stephen Beres begin soon .

For more information regarding this course, contact us at 844.716.1492.

Enroll Now:
https://fullsaildc3.com/catalog/courses/craft-of-cinematography-mastering-visual-language


____________________

844.716.1492 | fullsail.edu

3300 University Boulevard | Winter Park, FL 32792

Full Sail DC3 is a dynamic, digital-centric education platform that offers online, continuing education courses. DC3 is a department of Full Sail University, and backed by over 45 years of Full Sail University experience in entertainment media and emerging technology, as well as more than a decade of experience delivering compelling online education.

Subject: Dont Miss Out: Limited-Time Offer to Apply for Free
Body Text:
Save $75 with an application fee waiver

Apply Now <http://apply.gse.upenn.edu/apply?utm_campaign=spring-25&utm_content=fee-waiver&utm_medium=email&utm_source=organic>



                                      Candace,                                    

                                      We're excited to see your interest in the Learning Analytics and Artificial Intelligence (Online) M.S.Ed. program! Direct path to become a Jay Shetty certified coach by August

Subject: [Day 1 Assignments] 5-Day Gen AI Intensive
Body Text:
Kaggle


Hello Candace,

 Today's Assignments

1. Complete the Intro Unit  Foundational Large Language Models & TextGeneration:


Listen to the summary podcast episode for this unit.
To complement the podcast, read the Foundational Large Language Models &Text Generation whitepaper.

2. Complete Unit 1  Prompt Engineering:


Listen to the summary podcast episode for this unit.
To complement the podcast, read the Prompt Engineering whitepaper.
Complete these codelabs on Kaggle:

Prompting fundamentals
Evaluation and structured data

Make sure you phone verify your Kaggle account before starting, it'snecessary for the codelabs.
Want to have an interactive conversation? Try adding the whitepapers toNotebookLM.

 What You'll Learn

Today you'll explore the evolution of LLMs, from transformers to techniqueslike fine-tuning and inference acceleration. You'll also get trained in theart of prompt engineering for optimal LLM interaction and evaluating LLMs.

The first codelab will walk you through getting started with the Gemini 2.0API and cover several prompt techniques including how different parametersimpact the prompts. In the second codelab, you will also learn how toevaluate the response of LLMs using autoraters and structured output.

 Reminders


Tomorrow at 11:00 AM PT, Paige Bailey is hosting the first livestream onour YouTube channel to discuss the assignments with the course authors andother special guests from Google. Tomorrow's guests are Warren Barkley,Logan Kilpatrick, Kieran Milan, Anant Nawalgaria, Irina Sigler and MatVelloso.
Discord is the best place to ask questions  specifically in the#5dgai-question-forum channel. In addition to other participants, severalGooglers are there to help. During the livestream, we'll also pick somequestions from Discord to discuss. You'll get Kaggle swag if your questionis chosen!
We also have a troubleshooting guide for the codelabs. Be sure to checkthere for solutions to common problems.
We want this course community to be positive and supportive. Please followKaggle's community guidelines found here.

Happy learning and see you tomorrow!

The Kaggle Team








Google

 2025 Kaggle, Inc 1600 Amphitheatre Pkwy Mountain View, CA 94043

Subject: How to get more of the 3 Ps Candace
Body Text:
Hey again Candace,



This morning I wrote to you about finding and aligning with your 3 Ps:



1. Purpose

2. Passion

3. Process



Because if any one of these is out of alignment in your life



Youll always feel that emptiness that nothing quite fulfills you.



That maybe youre on the wrong path



And no matter how technically successful you are - you feel like you could be doing more.



So many of my students came to my coaching school because they were out of alignment with 1 or more of these 3 Ps



Many are successful CEOs, accountants, marketers, teachers, doctors and business owners.



Who feel no matter how high they climb - something is missing.



 They feel like they could do more for people.



 They feel like they could serve more.



 And they crave that feeling of making a real impact.



Through being part of my school



 They found their purpose in coaching.



 They fed their passion by serving others in this new, empowering way.



 And my school taught them the exact process they needed to coach others, ( https://pages.jayshettycoaching.com/ovsl-video-bau-e/?el=OVSL-email-three-ps-163-2&utm_campaign_name=JSCS%3A+Prospects+Week+163-3&utm_content_name=How+to+get+more+of+the+%E2%80%9C3+P%E2%80%99s%E2%80%9D+Name&utm_medium_name=email_action&utm_source_name=customer.io ) step by step, with support from my team.



Now



Ive got new spaces that just opened for students who want me to show them how to coach and bring more of the 3 Ps into their lives between now and August.



If you want to live a life that aligns with your purpose and feeds your passions



Click here to learn more about my unique coaching process ( https://pages.jayshettycoaching.com/ovsl-video-bau-e/?el=OVSL-email-three-ps-163-2&utm_campaign_name=JSCS%3A+Prospects+Week+163-3&utm_content_name=How+to+get+more+of+the+%E2%80%9C3+P%E2%80%99s%E2%80%9D+Name&utm_medium_name=email_action&utm_source_name=customer.io )(and how you could become one of my students) ( https://pages.jayshettycoaching.com/ovsl-video-bau-e/?el=OVSL-email-three-ps-163-2&utm_campaign_name=JSCS%3A+Prospects+Week+163-3&utm_content_name=How+to+get+more+of+the+%E2%80%9C3+P%E2%80%99s%E2%80%9D+Name&utm_medium_name=email_action&utm_source_name=customer.io )

Subject: Hype Is Not A Data Strategy
Body Text:
View this post on the web at https://seattledataguy.substack.com/p/hype-is-not-a-data-strategy

Hi, fellow future and current Data Leaders; Ben here 
Its hard to ignore all the FOMO and hype. For over the past decade weve been hearing terms like data-driven and how companies that dont adopt data science will fall behind. Of course data and AI can be used to improve your workflows but it can also become a distraction.
But before we jump in, I wanted to share a bit about Estuary [ https://substack.com/redirect/1ad3d458-1e44-4d0d-87c4-2b254c984a37?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], a platform I've used to help make clients' data workflows easier and am an adviser for. Estuary helps teams easily move data in real-time or on a schedule, from databases and SaaS apps to data lakes and warehouses, empowering data leaders to focus on strategy and impact rather than getting bogged down by infrastructure challenges. If you want to simplify your data workflows, check them out today.
Now lets jump into the article!
Almost every conversation I have with a data leader eventually leads to the same phrase: Our industry is so far behind. But if everyone is behind, whos actually ahead?
The obvious answers are companies like Uber, Facebook, Netflix, and Google. But those are the ones setting the curve. Comparing your industry to companies that live and die by how well they use data is never going to be a fair fight.
Most companies, no matter how much they want to, dont make money off of data. They sell coffee, sneakers, or warehouse goods. Data might help, but its not the product. And while its true that margins, logistics, and brand can all benefit from good data, the real challenge isnt just collecting it, its making it useful.
Thats where most teams get stuck. Instead of working with the business to solve real problems, they default to solving the technical ones they already know how to fix.
The 1% Effect
In a recent Data Leaders Playbook monthly meeting, someone brought up what might be called the 1% effect, or the social media effect. It used to be that your reference point was your neighbors when it came to wealth and status. 
You had a limited view of what people had, wanted, or aspired to. Then came Instagram. Now it feels like everyone is flying private, wearing Patek Philippe watches, and vacationing in the Maldives. Suddenly, that becomes the new normal.
The same thing happens in tech. We read Netflix [ https://substack.com/redirect/55c60560-a894-420e-9a58-f8d4c6286894?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] and Uber [ https://substack.com/redirect/258917f9-d892-44fd-bf79-913c03e2704f?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] engineering blogs and start believing we need the same setup. But those companies have invested far more than most of companies ever will in data. Their survival depends on how well they use data. Its not a derivative or a nice to have. It is the business.
One of the things that still sets Facebook apart, at least from the marketers I talk to, is how absurdly effective it is. I have friends who literally have to delete Instagram just to stop themselves from buying everything they see. That level of impact doesnt come from basic dashboards. 
And heres the kicker: I was speaking with several big tech engineers the other day, and they were discussing several processes that still required spreadsheets, which were maintained by a single person (every company has this issue!).
So yes, those engineering blogs are fun to read. But chasing their architecture without their resources is often the first step into a FOMO-fueled strategy.
The Consulting Industrial Complex
Its not just the blogs. The consulting industrial complex has been peddling FOMO well really since the started. Like clockwork, the moment a new term or tool hits the scene, the white papers start rolling out. And of course they might develop a few of their own acronyms. Regardless, the message is always the same: act fast or fall behind.
Why the rush? Because consultants benefit the most. Theyre selling the idea of what shovels could find. Many times not even delivering the shovels. But just like we hoard online courses well never finish, executives love to romanticize what the future could look like if the consultants actually delivered on their vision.
Beyond the fantasy, theres pressure. Execs often need to sell ideas, good or bad, to the board and public markets. Think Bear Stearns before their collapse. Or Nikes recent digital transformation push [ https://substack.com/redirect/c33dba63-16f2-4921-896c-8b4544297fed?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], which turned into a cautionary tale despite all the right buzzwords. (To be fair, the Nike story is more complicatedI mentioned it here because digital transformation was a consultant favorite.)
The C-Suite has every incentive to make things look like theyre going great. If the plan succeeds, they take the credit. If it flops, they spin the storybecause admitting failure means owning the millions spent on consultants and implementation that led nowhere.
But lets be honest: its not just the consultants. We technical folk dont always help, either.
SeattleDataGuys Newsletter is a reader-supported publication. To receive new posts and support my work, consider becoming a free or paid subscriber.
Playing Pretend
The irony of all of this is we often build far more complex systems than we actually need. Data teams think they can cargo cult their way to success,just put all the tools in the right order.
If they just use Iceberg [ https://substack.com/redirect/af179998-b2c6-4aa8-a53c-316fb9e53e2f?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ].
If they just use Presto [ https://substack.com/redirect/b557aff2-9bfd-46b6-ab01-0a82df66cb51?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ].
If they just use dbt [ https://substack.com/redirect/add05892-aa2c-465b-8cf4-f351843b567e?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ].
Then, all their problems will magically be solved. Like chanting the right magical phrase.
Instead, they end up building a 10-layer-deep data stack powering five SQL [ https://substack.com/redirect/c85dd419-ed76-4432-a372-645c29f90788?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] queries and two reports.
But hey, the data science team is working on some awesome AI projects! Using cutting-edge models.
Waitnope, theyre using XGBoost [ https://substack.com/redirect/5adecc82-534a-4607-962c-6bc61a86cdbb?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
(And to be clear, theres nothing wrong with that.)
Theres also nothing wrong with building simple solutions and delivering results. As Ive talked about before, Ive walked into so many projects where it was obvious the previous developer was building their own personal statue of Nebuchadnezzar. Something grand and complex, but ultimately for themselves. A selfish creation designed more to polish an ego than solve a problem.
Or maybe, like me, they just couldnt shake the constant, quiet panic in the back of their mind that they were falling behind.
Hype Is Not A Strategy
Maybe no one wants to say it out loud, but most companies are still struggling with the same issues I saw when I first started out, and the same issues seasoned data experts still see every day:
Data silos that block decision-making
Reporting workflows that rely on copying and pasting between Google Sheets(this includes at companies like Amazon, Google, Facebook, and all the companies youd assume would be Excel free)
Simple column or table requests that take weeks to deliver
No clear definitions for terms like "active customer" or "readmission"
Hiring challenges, such as finding the right people, or letting go of the wrong ones
There are plenty of ways automation [ https://substack.com/redirect/703b9143-66f0-47a0-a2fa-fe43a7b0c012?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], AI, and tooling can help. But please, dont just slap a chatbot on everything. 
Instead, try this:
Focus on outcome-driven wins: Everyone wants to sound impressive and talk about the shiny new tools theyre implementing. But "impressing people is utterly different from being truly impressive." (Ego Is the Enemy [ https://substack.com/redirect/c37c3309-4ca8-4d4f-a302-5545008ce6eb?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ].) Real impact often comes from doing tedious work well. It might not land you on a conference stage, but it works.Alright we might be reducing some of that tedious work thanks to AI.)
Invest in culture and process before tech: You could build the perfect stack or roll out some custom AI model. But if your company culture doesnt support using data and curiosity, all that effort will collect dust.
Adopt an "always be learning" mindset: Im not an AI denialist. You should absolutely explore how emerging tech can improve your workflows. But adding chatbots everywhere without a plan? Thats not innovation, its nostalgia for 2016.
Final Thoughts
When I posted something similar to this article on LinkedIn, someone replied:
If you dont have the money and resources of Google/Facebook, you shouldnt compare yourself to them. Figuring out your own path is more personal but potentially more rewarding as well.
Honestly? It sounds like self-help advice. And maybe thats the point. Because when youre leading a company and start feeling behind, your first instinct is to chase somethinganythingthat makes it look like youre catching up.
For many right now, that something is AI. Where can we plug it in? How fast can we launch it? What can we point to that says were doing something futuristic?
And consultancies know it. Theyll sell you the dream, fast. Like those get rich quick schemes being hawked on Youtube ads for twelve easy payments of $100,000.99.
But instead of figuring out how to drive real impact with the data you already have, you risk chasing an ideal your business wouldnt adopt even if you executed it flawlessly.
Take a breath. You might already have smart, capable people on your team who can help you figure out where data and automation can actually move the needle.
As always, thanks for reading.
Join My Data Engineering And Data Science Discord
If youre looking to talk more about data engineering, data science, breaking into your first job, and finding other like minded data specialists. Then you should join the Seattle Data Guy discord!
We are now over 8000 members!
Join My Technical Consultants Community
If youre a data consultant or considering becoming one then you should join the Technical Freelancer Community! We have over 1700 members!
Youll find plenty of free resources you can access to expedite your journey as a technical consultant as well as be able to talk to other consultants about questions you may have!
Articles Worth Reading
There are thousands of new articles posted daily all over the web! I have spent a lot of time sifting through some of these articles as well as TechCrunch and companies tech blog and wanted to share some of my favorites!
How To Automate PDF Data Extraction 
If you work in data, then at some point in your career, youll likely need to parse data from a PDF.
You might need to parse thousands of PDFs in order to pull out invoice information.
Or maybe you need to parse financial filing documents such as 10-Ks.
This can seem challenging at first. Afterall, PDFs are not CSVs or some form of other more structured file.
But it doesnt have to be. There are several tools you can use that range from Python libraries to out of the box solutions. All of which can make parsing and analyzing data from PDFs far easier.
In this article I wanted to cover how you can use Python to scrape data from a PDF but also how you can analyze data from a PDF without ever using Python.
So, lets dive in!
Read More Here [ https://substack.com/redirect/c1276fca-9433-453f-991a-68c4f56c2ea1?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Postgres to MotherDuck: Offload Analytics Without Slowing Down
Your app runs on PostgreSQL. It is fast, reliable, and great for transactions. But once your team asks for analytics (like user signups, sales trends, or product performance), you might start running complex queries against the same database.
That is when the issues begin.
A query like SELECT COUNT(*) FROM orders WHERE created_at > now() - interval '30 days' gets slow. Dashboards time out. CPU usage climbs. The app feels sluggish because the same system handles transactional and analytical workloads.
You could scale up or add read replicas, which only delays the problem. The real issue is trying to do analytics on a database that was built for transactions.
This article shows a better approach. You can stream data from Postgres into MotherDuck, a fast analytics engine built on DuckDB. With Change Data Capture (CDC) and Estuary Flow, you get a continuous sync of your data, so you can run heavy queries in MotherDuck without touching your production database.
Read More Here [ https://substack.com/redirect/605c56cc-8476-4621-be76-411772ab6177?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]

Subject: [Day 4 Assignments] 5-Day Gen AI Intensive
Body Text:
Kaggle


Hello Candace,

 Today's Assignments

Complete Unit 4 - Domain-Specific LLMs:


Listen to the summary podcast episode for this unit.
To complement the podcast, read the Solving Domain-Specific Problems UsingLLMs whitepaper.
Complete these codelabs on Kaggle:


Tune a Gemini model for a custom task
Use Google Search data in generation

Want to have an interactive conversation? Try adding the whitepaper toNotebookLM.

 What You'll Learn

In today's reading, you'll delve into the creation and application ofspecialized LLMs like SecLM and MedLM/Med-PaLM, with insights from theresearchers who built them.

In the codelabs, you'll learn how to add real-world data to a model usingGoogle Search and then visualize it with plotting tools via the Live API.You will also learn how to fine-tune a custom Gemini model using your ownlabeled data to solve custom tasks.

 Reminders and Announcements:


Find the complete list of scheduled livestreams and past recordings here.
The next livestream with Paige Bailey is tomorrow at 11 AM PT / 7 PM CET /11:30 PM IST. Click here to join! Livestream guests: Donny Cheung, ScottCoull, Ewa Dominowska, Chris Grier, Anant Nawalgaria and Karthik Raman.
Be sure to ask all your questions about the podcast, readings, and codelabsin the #5dgai-question-forum channel on Discord. You'll get Kaggle swag ifyour question is chosen for discussion during the livestream.

Happy learning and see you tomorrow!

The Kaggle Team

Subject: From stuck to starting TWO non-profits
Body Text:
This week is the 5th Anniversary of the Jay Shetty Certification School. 



And as I was reflecting on our journey so far, I was reading back through some of our 3,100+ students stories



This one really captures what we do here:

Your invitation to join my mission ( https://pages.jayshettycoaching.com/5-years/?el=5th-bday-email-158-3&utm_campaign_name=JSCS%3A+Prospects+Week+158-3&utm_content_name=From+stuck+to+starting+TWO+non-profits&utm_medium_name=email_action&utm_source_name=customer.io )
Neffeterias story is like so many others.



She was struggling to find her identity.



And had hit a roadblock in her career.



She knew her purpose was to help girls who struggled to connect with their parentsbut she couldnt seem to find her path to do that.



Then



Everything changed when she joined the Jay Shetty Certification School.



The skills and techniques she learned not only helped her become a professional coach.



But also create TWO non-profits to help girls.



AND shes using what shes learned to have deeper connections with her own daughters at home too.



This is exactly why we started this school 5 years ago.



If you feel like Neffeterias story resonates with you.



And you want to discover your own path and write your own coaching story in 2025.

direction.

).

(

Subject: What We Get Wrong About Procrastination
Body Text:
Procrastination is an emotion regulation problem, not
a time management problem



Hey Candace,

Hope you had a good weekend 

If you're subscribed to LifeNotes (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/xmue9nmx3rt6hpdrn2mc5h2833kllfn/m2h7h6u3q0zdzdal/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL25ld3NsZXR0ZXIv
), you might've noticed that I sent it a couple of days late this
week (sorry ). Honestly, I don't really have a good excuse but
part of the delay can actually be explained by the topic at the
heart of today's email - procrastination.

Procrastination is one of those terms that comes up a lot in the
productivity / self-development space. It's one of the core
issues holding people back from reaching their goals, hitting
their targets or even just getting stuff done. And I'm not immune
to it either - my troubles with my own newsletter are evidence of
that this weekend 

But in thinking about this email I was reminded of a quote about
procrastination from Dr. Tim Pychyl that completely reframed how
I thought about the phenomenon:

Procrastination is an emotion regulation problem, not a time
management problem.
I actually interviewed Dr. Pychyl on my podcast a couple of years
ago, which you can watch here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/xmue9nmx3rt6hpdrn2mc5h2833kllfn/7qh7h2u96p5r5eu9/aHR0cHM6Ly95b3V0dS5iZS9kR0lVdFZ1N3c0WT9zaT1CdENWa1k5TDA4MGVVVWdt
), but what I found particularly interesting about this quote is
that he's suggesting that procrastination is less about poor
organisation or lack of willpower and more about avoiding
uncomfortable emotions.

For years, most of us have been told that procrastination is a
discipline issue - that if we just planned our time better, set
clearer deadlines, and just tried harder, wed stop putting
things off. But this quote suggests something different.

Procrastination isnt about laziness or lack of willpower - its
actually a way for our brains to avoid the stress, fear, or
discomfort associated with a task. And if procrastination is
driven by emotion rather than time management, then fixing it
requires a different approach. Instead of focusing on scheduling
or willpower, the goal should be to identify and address the
emotions behind the avoidance.

But what does all this mean in practice? Well, heres a simple
process that might help, which takes into account this new way of
seeing procrastination:

1 Notice when youre procrastinating.

The moment you catch yourself avoiding something, pause and ask:
What am I feeling right now?

2 Identify the emotion.

Are you anxious about failing? Overwhelmed by the complexity?
Bored out of your mind? Naming the emotion helps reduce its hold
over you.

3 Reframe the task.

* If self-doubt is stopping you, remind yourself that
imperfection is okay. Just get started.
* If anxiety is stopping you, break the task into smaller, less
intimidating steps.
* If boredom is stopping you, make the task more engaging. Gamify
it, set a timer, or add a reward.

4 Take the smallest possible action.

When in doubt, just start, even if its tiny. Write one sentence.
Read one paragraph. Set a five-minute timer. Action reduces
anxiety, and once you begin, momentum takes over.

Sometimes, procrastination is telling us something deeper. That
the task itself might not be right for us and if you find
yourself constantly avoiding something, its worth asking:

* Does this align with my goals? Maybe youre forcing yourself to
do something that doesnt actually matter (this is why Vision is
one of the two key pillars at the heart of LifeOS (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/xmue9nmx3rt6hpdrn2mc5h2833kllfn/z2hgh7uekrxqv9fz/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2xpZmVvcy8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPXByb2NyYXN0aW5hdGlvbl8xNCZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9cHJvZHVjdGl2ZW5vdGVz
) ).
* Am I putting too much pressure on myself? High expectations can
make starting feel impossible. Lowering the stakes can make a
huge difference.
* Is there another way to do this? Maybe the method youre using
isnt working, and a different approach would make it easier.

By recognising why were avoiding a task and adjusting our
mindset, we can make progress without relying on sheer willpower.

For me, it's often just putting too much pressure on LifeNotes
needing to be particularly valuable or insightful which causes me
to procrastinate but whenever I just start writing or talking
with Voicepal (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/xmue9nmx3rt6hpdrn2mc5h2833kllfn/6qhehoul56emgwf9/aHR0cHM6Ly9nby5hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL3ZvaWNlcGFsL3Byb2R1Y3RpdmVub3Rlcw==
), the ideas tend to flow.

Let me know if this reframe is helpful for getting through those
moments of procrastination and whether you've found any other
approaches to be particularly effective yourself - hit reply and
let me know :)

Otherwise, have a great week as we head into the second half of
April 

Ali xx

P.S - in case you missed the Spring Reset Workshop at the end of
last month, I just wanted to let you know that you can catch the
recording here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/xmue9nmx3rt6hpdrn2mc5h2833kllfn/kkhmh2un52vkq2uk/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL3NwcmluZy1yZXNldC13b3Jrc2hvcC1yZXdhdGNo
)

Subject: I will start once [insert excuse]
Body Text:
Hey there!

Over the past 2 days, 50+ writers have joined Ghostwriter GPT and
started to introduce themselves to the community.

However, we noticed you havent secured your copy yet.

Obviously, no pressurewere actually glad youre being
thoughtful about this because thats a pattern weve seen in our
most successful students.

That said, we also want to make sure you have all the information
you need to make the right investment in yourself.

So in this email, wed like to address the single biggest
question weve gotten since we launched the product a few days
ago.

-----------------------------------------------------------------
But Cole Im not ready to join Ghostwriter GPT yet. I need to
[insert excuse] first!!!
-----------------------------------------------------------------

Now, after coaching 1,500+ ghostwriters weve noticed a pattern:

When someone tells us theyre not ready to start their
ghostwriting business, theyre usually thinking about one of
these concerns:

* I dont have enough expertise in any specific area

* I need to figure out my niche before I can use these tools

* I should build more credibility first

* I need to research the market more thoroughly

* I dont feel confident enough to position myself as an expert

* I should practice writing more before offering services

But the truth is

You dont need to have it all figured out to get started.
---------------------------------------------------------

Its actually the oppositeyou need to get started so you can
start to figure things out.

I get it, though. I (Dickie) used to be addicted to planning
myself. My brain loved the cheap dopamine of gathering books to
read, tasks to complete, and videos to watch. But when it came to
taking action, the euphoric rush faded.

But my addiction to planning finally ended when I heard this
story of two men learning to fish:



----------------------------------
The Tale of 2 Men Learning To Fish
----------------------------------

Once upon, 2 men set out to learn how to fish.

The first fisherman was a planner. He heads straight to the
marina to buy the best fishing boat money can buy. Then, he specs
out an expensive, custom, carbon-fiber fishing rod. And from
there, he spends hundreds of hours reading up and watching videos
on everything there is to know about fishing.

* Casting angles
* Weather patterns
* Baiting techniques

You name it, hes bought the book on it. And of course, hes
watching the fishing channel every night for hours, learning from
the best of the best.

A few months laterafter months of diligent preparationhe
finally feels ready to fish. So the next day, he heads out on the
lake in his new boat with his fancy rod and wealth of fishing
experience built up over the last few months.

But six hours in, nothing. Not even a nibble.

-----------------
Sowhat happened?
-----------------

Turns out, the second fisherman had already sucked the lake dry.

On day one, the second fisherman grabbed a shitty rod, sliced up
a hot dog, and went to the lake. The first day, nothing. So he
moved to a new spot. Second day, nothing. So then he moved again.
And on the third day? His first nibble.

>From there it was time to iterate. And every day after, he honed
his technique. He found a baiting technique that worked a bit
better. Or a new lake with a few more fish. And after three weeks
of iteration, he found the winning combination.

Before long, he was hauling in hundreds of fish every day. To
keep up with his daily haul, he hired a small team to help him.
And from there, he opened a restaurant with fat margins to sell
his fresh fish.

He did all of this while the first fisherman sat around gathering
gear.

The moral of this story?

Get to action as quickly as possible. When you find yourself
gathering gear, stop. Instead, grab a shitty rod and start
fishing.

--------------------------
Heres the nuance, though
--------------------------

Theres 2 ways you can go about taking action:

You can get started on your own, for surebut thats the slower,
more painful way to do it.

The alternative?

Join Ghostwriter GPT, get a proven roadmap to start taking action
on the right things, and unlock our proven prompts to accelerate
the whole process.

The beautiful part iswith this system youll have everything you
need to actually get started. And once you join, well help you
put together a roadmap to ensure youre taking action on the
RIGHT things from day one via a (free) 1:1 Implementation Call.

No more months of preparation.

No more analysis paralysis.

Just a clear path forward with proven frameworks & systems that
work.

---------------------------------------------
So, ready to stop planning and start fishing?
---------------------------------------------

Then, its time to stop planning and start doing.

Dont spend the next 6 months preparing to start your
ghostwriting business while others are already landing clients
and building unstoppable momentum.

Youre closeand wed love to help you hit your goals.

*****************************************************************
Click here to get Ghostwriter GPT and start taking action TODAY.
(
https://click.convertkit-mail.com/e5uw7qqv2wc7hlnpplnf8h8dgz222blh2xnz2/owh2xzw9twuwlr42rrsq/aHR0cHM6Ly9kZmwwLnVzL3MvZjk5NzYxZWU_ZW09YWljb2FjaGluZzIwMjUlNDBnbWFpbC5jb20=
)
*****************************************************************

But dont forget: Ghostwriter GPT is only available for 3 more
days. After that, its gone forever.

So, dont wait too long to secure your spot!

See you inside,

Cole & Dickie

PS - 50+ ghostwriters have already taken the plunge and joined
Ghostwriter GPT.

And we have an awesome mix of beginner and more experienced
writers in the community.

For example, Adam here is ready to build a profitable
ghostwriting side hustle. But he joined Ghostwriter GPT to make

Subject: You Might Be Thinking About Ideation Wrong
Body Text:
Hey Candace,

Before we get started, I wanted to let you know that Ive just
announced that Ill be hosting a completely free workshop - the
2025 Spring Reset - on Saturday 29th March at 1400 GMT. Ive been
running these free events every quarter for the past 12 months
because this sort of reflection forms a key part of my philosophy
on productivity, life and fulfilment and ultimately I just want
to encourage everyone to take a more intentional approach to
their goals instead of just seeing it as a January activity  If
you're interested, you'll be automatically registered with one
click by clicking here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/0vu4o3k67va9h9xwzz3tlhvlgq555fn/owh2dwx3iwuwkn7v38uq/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL3NwcmluZy1yZXNldC1jb25maXJtYXRpb24v
)  (or if you'd like to find out more information before signing
up please click here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/0vu4o3k67va9h9xwzz3tlhvlgq555fn/m2h7h6u3g97pkoal/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL3NwcmluZy1yZXNldC0yMDI1Lw==
)).

Anyway, onto the main email and today I wanted to briefly talk
about the ever-challenging issue of idea generation.

The question of what you should make videos about is probably the
second most common query that I get from beginners - only really
coming after the related question of what should my channel be
about? 

When I look back on my early YouTube days, I was inspired by
three YouTubers in particular - Simon Clark, Sara Dietschy, and
Peter McKinnon - and my channel began as a result of me trying to
imitate all of them. I loved the way Simon leant into the
academic side of things talking about all the stuff he found
interesting. Sara spoke about tech in a really cool and engaging
way, and then Peter created vibey and very charismatic tutorials,
so I wanted to do something similar within my own content.

But I didnt simply copy what they were doing. Instead, I put my
own spin on things by talking about medical school admissions,
because that was my own area of expertise at the time. Even now,
I still watch lots of other YouTube videos, listen to podcasts,
and read books to curate my own content.

The truth is, especially when it comes to creative work,
everything builds on something that came before - in fact, this
is one of the key takeaways in the book Steal Like An Artist by
Austin Kleon (great read by the way ) and also something that
Sara herself mentioned when I interviewed her back in 2020.

So if youre trying to come up with the next best viral video
idea thats totally unique and never been seen before on YouTube,
then youre approaching the process of ideation in the wrong way.
Instead, and especially at the start of your journey, you need to
let go of this pressure, start embracing the influence that other
creators have on you, and build systems behind your creativity.

For example, one of the methods for generating new video ideas
that I teach to my PTYA (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/0vu4o3k67va9h9xwzz3tlhvlgq555fn/dphehmue4kmgz0il/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL3BhcnQtdGltZS15b3V0dWJlci1hY2FkZW15P3V0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1Zb3VyZSUyMFRoaW5raW5nJTIwQWJvdXQlMjBJZGVhdGlvbiUyMFdyb25nJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1jcmVhdG9ybm90ZXM=
) students is The Birdsong Technique.

When youre a content consumer, you sort of passively enjoy the
things that other people create. But as soon as you step into the
shoes of the creator, everything shifts. You begin thinking how
can I use this content in my next video and start seeing ideas
literally everywhere.

Its just like birdsong. Most of the time their sounds fade into
the background noise of everyday life, but if youre really
listening out for it, you can distinguish different birds and
appreciate their incredible symphony.

Put simply, The Birdsong Technique is about recognising that
there are ideas everywhere in everything that we consume
everyday. So next time youre doom scrolling or mindlessly
watching YouTube videos, try shifting your mindset from consumer
to creator **by asking yourself these questions:

* Is there something interesting in this piece of content that I
can use as a new video idea?
* What do I love about this content that I could incorporate into
my own videos? 
* How can I add my own twist to this? 

Im sure youll be amazed at how many ideas you come up with, and
Id love to hear some of them. Hit reply and send me some of your
ideas.

Next week, Ill let you in on some of the struggles Ive been
having recently when it comes to filtering through my ideas and
deciding which ones would actually make for good YouTube videos -
that's a task that never gets easier 

Have a great week :)

Ali xx

P.S

As you probably know by now, systems are a big part of my whole
philosophy around becoming a Part-Time YouTuber and we've just
relaunched YouTubeOS (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/0vu4o3k67va9h9xwzz3tlhvlgq555fn/e0hph0u7pe2g97t7/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL3lvdXR1YmUtb3MvP3V0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1Zb3VyZSUyMFRoaW5raW5nJTIwQWJvdXQlMjBJZGVhdGlvbiUyMFdyb25nJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1jcmVhdG9ybm90ZXM=
) - a content production hub that you can use as the foundation
of your own production system. You get access to a load of
templates plus a few lessons from the main course itself, some of
which cover idea generation actually 

 Want to start a YouTube channel? Go here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/0vu4o3k67va9h9xwzz3tlhvlgq555fn/7qh7h2u9k8m7vwt9/aHR0cHM6Ly9nby5wdHlhLmNvbS9wdHlhLWJsLWZvb3Rlcg==
).

Unsubscribe from PTYA updates (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/0vu4o3k67va9h9xwzz3tlhvlgq555fn/n2h7v3v6bquv8gkpwes0/aHR0cHM6Ly9wdHlhLmNvbS9zb3JyeS10by1zZWUteW91LWdvLw==
) |

) |
